<P><A NAME="lr2_estsigma"></A><B>How is &sigma; obtained?</B></P>

<P>The parameters &sigma;, &lambda;<sub>1</sub>, &sigma;<sub>x<sub>1</sub></sub>, &sigma;<sub>y<sub>1</sub></sub>
and &rho;<sub>1</sub> are all interrelated (see <A HREF="pshe23av.htm#ref4">Dupont and
Plummer 1998</A>).   You may estimate &sigma; directly.  However, you may also
estimate &sigma; indirectly by entering estimates of one of the following
sets of parameters from pilot data.  </P>

<P>&sigma;<sub>x<sub>1</sub></sub><sub>1</sub>, &sigma;<sub>y<sub>1</sub></sub> and &lambda;<sub>1</sub></P>

<P>&sigma;<sub>x</sub>, &rho;<sub>1</sub> and &lambda;<sub>1</sub> </P>

<P>It is important that the preceding all come from the same pilot data.  The values of
&sigma;, &lambda;<sub>1</sub>, &sigma;<sub>x<sub>1</sub></sub>, &sigma;<sub>y<sub>1</sub></sub>
and &rho;<sub>1</sub> used to estimate &sigma; need not be the same as the values of
these statistics for your planned study.</P>

<P>&lambda;<sub>1</sub> is the slope estimate in the control group (group1)</P>

<P>&sigma;<sub>x<sub>1</sub></sub> is the standard deviation of the independent variable for the control subjects</P>

<P>&sigma;<sub>y<sub>1</sub></sub> is the standard deviation of the dependent variable in the control group (group 1)</P>

<P>&rho;<sub>1</sub> is the correlation coefficient between the dependent and independent variables for the control subjects</P>

